{
  "texts": [
    "The occurrence of a larger number of reversible motions on the surface of obstacles provides CAPs with more opportunities to explore the surrounding space.",
    "Consequently, this increased exploration enhances the likelihood of CAPs successfully hopping to the next row of obstacles.",
    "Notably, our results demonstrate a strong positive correlation between N and the effective diffusivity of CAPs.",
    "A larger ω 0 (small r) produces a shorter t 2 (Fig. 6), that is, shorter t slide, corresponding to larger μ and N, and more hopping.",
    "More hopping usually produces a faster diffusion except that the trajectory forms a nearly closed loop, see the strongly caged motion in Fig."
  ]
}